  "prompt": "How do PHP developers access a database on Google App Engine?",
  "response": "For PHP developers working with Google App Engine (GAE), there are a few different approaches to accessing databases:\n\n1. Cloud SQL (Recommended)\n```php\n// Using PDO for MySQL connection\n$username = getenv('CLOUDSQL_USERNAME');\n$password = getenv('CLOUDSQL_PASSWORD');\n$dbName = getenv('CLOUDSQL_DATABASE');\n$connectionName = getenv('CLOUDSQL_CONNECTION_NAME');\n\n// For Unix socket connection\n$socket = \"/cloudsql/{$connectionName}\";\n$dsn = \"mysql:unix_socket={$socket};dbname={$dbName}\";\n\ntry {\n    $conn = new PDO($dsn, $username, $password);\n    $conn->setAttribute(PDO::ATTR_ERRMODE, PDO::ERRMODE_EXCEPTION);\n} catch (PDOException $e) {\n    // Handle connection error\n    echo \"Connection failed: \" . $e->getMessage();\n}\n```\n\n2. Firestore (NoSQL database)\n```php\nuse Google\\Cloud\\Firestore\\FirestoreClient;\n\n// Initialize Firestore client\n$firestore = new FirestoreClient();\n\n// Add a document\n$collection = $firestore->collection('users');\n$collection->add([\n    'name' => 'John Doe',\n    'email' => 'john@example.com'\n]);\n\n// Query documents\n$query = $collection->where('name', '=', 'John Doe');\n$documents = $query->documents();\n```\n\n3. Using Google Cloud Datastore\n```php\nuse Google\\Cloud\\Datastore\\DatastoreClient;\n\n// Initialize Datastore client\n$datastore = new DatastoreClient();\n\n// Create an entity\n$taskKey = $datastore->key('Task');\n$task = $datastore->entity($taskKey, [\n    'description' => 'Buy milk',\n    'done' => false\n]);\n\n// Save the entity\n$datastore->insert($task);\n\n// Query entities\n$query = $datastore->query()\n    ->kind('Task')\n    ->filter('done', '=', false);\n\n$result = $datastore->runQuery($query);\n```\n\n4. Memorystore (Redis)\n```php\n$redis = new Redis();\n$redis->connect(\n    getenv('MEMORYSTORE_HOST'), \n    getenv('MEMORYSTORE_PORT')\n);\n\n// Set a value\n$redis->set('key', 'value');\n\n// Get a value\n$value = $redis->get('key');\n```\n\nKey Considerations:\n- Always use environment variables for sensitive connection details\n- Use prepared statements to prevent SQL injection\n- Handle connection errors gracefully\n- Use appropriate connection pooling strategies\n\nRecommended Best Practices:\n1. Use Cloud SQL for traditional relational databases\n2. Use Firestore for NoSQL document storage\n3. Use Datastore for scalable NoSQL data storage\n4. Use Memorystore for caching and fast data retrieval\n\nDependencies:\n- Install required Google Cloud PHP libraries:\n```bash\ncomposer require google/cloud-firestore\ncomposer require google/cloud-datastore\n```\n\nAuthentication:\n- Use application default credentials\n- Set up service account JSON for local development\n- Configure appropriate IAM permissions\n\nExample app.yaml configuration:\n```yaml\nruntime: php81\n\nenv_variables:\n  CLOUDSQL_CONNECTION_NAME: \"your-project:region:instance\"\n  CLOUDSQL_DATABASE: \"your_database\"\n  CLOUDSQL_USERNAME: \"your_username\"\n```\n\nEach approach has its pros and cons, so choose based on:\n- Data structure\n- Scalability needs\n- Read/write patterns\n- Consistency requirements\n\nRemember to handle connection timeouts, implement proper error handling, and use connection pooling for optimal performance on Google App Engine.",
